  abstract = {This chapter examines the notion that the calls for political restructuring and their resistance mirror the location in power relations of Nigerian ethnic groups. It shows the way in which some of the calls for political restructuring reflect changing political experiences and consequences, as well as the way political restructuring might be canvassed as a strategy for the pursuit of political ambition and in the process, substantiate its salience in the national question in Nigeria. Thus, in Nigeria's case, the contending concepts of the national question, the chapter concludes, express ethnic/class struggle and regional competition for resources. \copyright{} 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
