  abstract = {Official economic reality is steadily forming among the BRICS members in terms of both political and economic participation. In fact the five BRICS countries together encompass: \"i 50 per cent in terms of adjusted global GDP in the 2000\~n08 period; \"i the highest economic growth (over the past decade their economies have grown by 4.2 times compared with 61 per cent growth in developed countries); \"i 42 per cent of the world\'is population; \"i 26 per cent of the Earth\'is territory; \"i 20 per cent of the global economy; and \"i 14.6 per cent of the world\'is trade (BRICS, 2012c). The fast growing \"emodus operandi of the twenty-first century\'i, free from bureaucratic paraphernalia, is representative of a new kind of institution; the BRICS is such an institution, with its own political ambitions in terms of the changing global balance (Azambuja, 2010). All the BRICS countries are prominent members of the UN, G8 and G20 at both a global and regional scale. As \"ethe key pieces on the global chessboard\'i (Pereyra, 2012), the BRICS group \"ecould become a much more significant force in the world economy\'i and \"ewould dramatically change the list of the world\'is 10 largest economies\'i (BRICS, 2012b). \copyright{} Vai Io Lo and Mary Hiscock 2014.},
